recalls.Summary: ON CERTAIN PASSENGER VEHICLES, A CONDITION EXISTS THAT ALLOWS OIL TO LEAK FROM THE ALL-WHEEL DRIVE TRANSFER CASE.
recalls.Consequence: LOW OIL LEVELS IN THE TRANSFER CASE COULD CAUSE BEARING DAMAGE AND RESULT IN DRIVE TRAIN LOCKUP, INCREASING THE RISK OF A CRASH.
recalls.Remedy: DEALERS WILL INSPECT THE TRANSFER CASE FOR INDICATIONS OF OIL LEAKAGE OR DAMAGE.   VEHICLES THAT HAVE OIL LEAKAGE WILL HAVE THE TRANSFER CASE RESEALED AND RE-FILL THE TRANSFER CASE TO THE PROPER LEVEL, OR REPLACED THE TRANSFER CASE IF THERE IS EVIDENCE OF DAMAGE.  OWNER NOTIFICATION IS EXPECTED TO BEGIN DECEMBER 9, 2002.  OWNERS WHO TAKE THEIR VEHICLES TO AN AUTHORIZED DEALER ON AN AGREED UPON SERVICE DATE AND DO NOT RECEIVE THE FREE REMEDY WITHIN A REASONABLE TIME SHOULD CONTACT MITSUBISHI AMERICA AT 1-888-648-7820 OR MITSUBMISHI CARIBBEAN AT 1-787-251-8715.
recalls.Notes: MITSUBISHI RECALL BULLETIN NO. SR-02-003.   CUSTOMERS CAN ALSO CONTACT THE NATIONAL HIGHWAY TRAFFIC SAFETY ADMINISTRATION'S AUTO SAFETY HOTLINE AT 1-888-DASH-2-DOT (1-888-327-4236).

recalls.Summary: THE FRONT SAFETY BELT BUCKLE RELEASE BUTTONS CAN BREAK. THESE RED PLASTIC RELEASE BUTTONS ARE MARKED "PRESS." IF A BUTTON BREAKS, PIECES CAN FALL INTO THE BUCKLE ASSEMBLY CAUSING THE BUCKLE TO OPERATE IMPROPERLY.
recalls.Consequence: THE SAFETY BELTS WOULD NOT PROVIDE ADEQUATE PROTECTION TO AN OCCUPANT IN A VEHICLE CRASH.
recalls.Remedy: OWNERS SHOULD PROMPTLY CHECK THE CONDITION AND OPERATION OF BOTH FRONT SAFETY BELT BUCKLES AND CAREFULLY INSPECT THE RED RELEASE BUTTON FOR ANY BREAKS OR CRACKS. THEY SHOULD ENSURE THAT BOTH BUCKLES ARE OPERATING PROPERLY BY INSERTING EACH LATCH PLATE INTO ITS BUCKLE, TUGGING ON THE BELT TO MAKE SURE THE LATCH IS SECURELY LOCKED, AND THEN PRESSING THE RELEASE BUTTON. THE LATCH PLATE SHOULD POP OUT OF THE BUCKLE WHEN THE BUTTON IS PRESSED. IF EITHER RELEASE BUTTON SHOWS A SIGN OF BREAKING OR CRACKING OR IF EITHER BUCKLE FAILS TO OPERATE PROPERLY, OWNERS SHOULD PROMPTLY CONTACT THEIR AUTHORIZED DEALER TO SCHEDULE AN APPOINTMENT TO HAVE THE BUCKLE REPLACED OR REPAIRED, FREE OF CHARGE. THE MANUFACTURER IS DEVELOPING A REMEDY DESIGNED TO PREVENT FAILURE OF THE BUTTONS THAT ARE NOT CURRENTLY BROKEN.
recalls.Notes: SYSTEM: INTERIOR; SEAT BELTS; BELT BUCKLES.  VEHICLE DESCRIPTION: PASSENGER VEHICLES AND LIGHT DUTY TRUCKS AND VANS EQUIPPED WITH SAFETY BELTS MADE BY TAKATA CORPORATION.  NOTE: IF YOUR VEHICLE IS PRESENTED TO AN AUTHORIZED DEALER ON AN AGREED UPON SERVICE DATE AND THE REMEDY IS NOT PROVIDED FREE OF CHARGE WITHIN A REASONABLE TIME, PLEASE CONTACT MITSUBISHI AT 1-800-222-0037. ALSO CONTACT THE NATIONAL HIGHWAY TRAFFIC SAFETY ADMINISTRATION'S AUTO SAFETY HOTLINE AT 1-800-424-9393.

recalls.Summary: A CONDITION EXISTS THAT ALLOWS OIL TO LEAK FROM THE ALL WHEEL DRIVE TRANSFER CASE. LOW OIL LEVELS IN THE TRANSFER CASE CAN CAUSE BEARING DAMAGE AND FAILURE.
recalls.Consequence: BEARING FAILURE IN THE TRANSFER CASE CAN RESULT INPOWER TRAIN LOCKUP WITHOUT PRIOR WARNING, WHILE THE VEHICLE IS AT HIGHWAY SPEED.THIS COULD RESULT IN A LOSS OF VEHICLE CONTROL AND AN ACCIDENT.

complaints.summary: TL* THE CONTACT OWNS A 1991 MITSUBISHI 3000GT. UPON OPENING THE HOOD OF THE VEHICLE, THE CONTACT NOTICED FLUID LEAKING FROM THE TRANSFER CASE. THE CONTACT STATED THAT THE VEHICLE WAS REPAIRED PER NHTSA CAMPAIGN NUMBER: 93V033000 (POWER TRAIN), BUT IT FAILED TO REMEDY THE FAILURE. THE VEHICLE WAS TAKEN TO AN INDEPENDENT MECHANIC WHERE IT WAS DIAGNOSED THAT THE TRANSFER CASE BEARING WAS FAULTY. THE DEALER WAS NOT NOTIFIED. THE MANUFACTURER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE FAILURE. THE FAILURE MILEAGE WAS APPROXIMATELY 43,000.

TRANSFER CASE FAILED, DEALER OKED REPLACEMENT UNDER RECALL, A WEEK LATER THEY SAID THE PART THEY GOT WASN'T RIGHT AND THE TRANSMISSION OUTPUT SHAFT IS DAMAGED AND THEY CAN'T REPAIR. CONTACTED MITSUBISHI 4/6, BACK & FORTH VIA PHONE, ON 4/20 WAS TOLD "WAITING FOR A REPLY FROM LEGAL", WILL GET BACK TO ME IN COUPLE DAYS, NOTHING SINCE THEN. THE TC IS A RECALL AND THE TC FAILURE COMMONLY CAUSES OUTPUT SHAFT DAMAGE. THEY OKED THE RECALL, HAVE HAD THE CAR WEEKS, AND DONE NOTHING.

TL* THE CONTACT OWNS A 1991 MITSUBISHI 3000GT. THE CONTACT STATED THAT WHILE DRIVING APPROXIMATELY 75 MPH, ALL FOUR WHEELS SEIZED. THE VEHICLE WAS TAKEN TO THE DEALER WHERE THE CONTACT WAS INFORMED THAT A DEFECT IN THE TRANSFER CASE HAD CAUSED THE PROBLEM. THE CONTACT WAS INFORMED THAT THE VEHICLE WOULD NOT BE REPAIRED UNDER NHTSA CAMPAIGN NUMBER 02V143001(POWER TRAIN) BECAUSE THE DEFECT WAS REPAIRED BY THE PREVIOUS OWNER. THE MANUFACTURER WAS NOTIFIED AND NO SOLUTION WAS OFFERED. THE FAILURE MILEAGE WAS 112,000.

TL*THE CONTACT OWNS A 1991 MITSUBISHI 3000 GT.  WHILE MAKING A RIGHT TURN AT 25 MPH, THE POWERTRAIN LOCKED UP AND DISABLED THE VEHICLE.  THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED TO THE DEALER AND THEY STATED THAT IT WAS PREVIOUSLY REPAIRED IN 2005 ACCORDING TO NHTSA CAMPAIGN ID NUMBER 02V143001 (POWERTRAIN:TRANSFER CASE (4-WHEEL DRIVE)) AND WOULD NOT ASSUME LIABILITY.  THE VEHICLE HAS NOT BEEN REPAIRED.  THE CONTACT FILED A FORMAL COMPLAINT WITH THE MANUFACTURER.  THE CURRENT AND FAILURE MILEAGES WERE 140,000.
TRANSFERCASE ON 1991 MITSUBISHI 3000GT VR4 IS LEAKING TC FLUID AND MITSUBISHI HQ AND DEALERSHIP WILL NOT REPAIR/FIX PROBLEM AS STATED IN RECALL.  *TR

TL*THE CONTACT OWNS A 1991 MITSUBISHI 3000GT.  WHILE DRIVING OVER 45 MPH, BOTH REAR TIRES LOCKED UP AND THE VEHICLE CAME TO A COMPLETE STOP.  THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED TO THE CONTACT'S RESIDENCE.  THE VEHICLE IS NOT INCLUDED IN RECALL NUMBER 02V143001 (POWER TRAIN:TRANSFER CASE (4-WHEEL DRIVE)).  THE VEHICLE HAS NOT BEEN REPAIRED.  THE CURRENT AND FAILURE MILEAGES WERE 142,000.

SEAT BELTS IN 1991 DODGE STEALTH RT/TT DID NOT RETRACT!  THERE WAS  EASILY ENOUGH SLACK IN  SEAT BELT FOR ME TO HIT MY HEAD ON THE STEERING WHEEL.  MAKES ME FEEL VERY UNEASY ABOUT DRIVING MY CAR.  ALSO,  THE  SRS LIGHT IS ON.  THEY MAY BE RELATED.  *AK

TL*THE CONTACT OWNS A 1991 MITSUBISHI 3000 GT.  THERE IS A SAFETY RECALL ON THE VEHICLE, BUT THE CONTACT'S VIN IS EXCLUDED.  THE CONTACT STATED THAT THE TRANSFER CASE HAS A LEAK.  THE WEATHER AND DRIVING SPEED WERE NOT FACTORS AND THE VEHICLE HAS NOT FAILED SINCE.  THE CURRENT MILEAGE IS 71,000 AND FAILURE MILEAGE WAS APPROXIMATELY 70, 985.
SEAT BELT DOES NOT FULLY RETRACT, LEAVING SLACK ON THE BELT. THE SLACK HAS TO BE MANUALLY REMOVED. THIS CAN CAUSE SERIOUS INJURY IN A CRASH.  *JB

I HAVE PREVIOUSLY ENTERED A COMPLAINT CONCERNING THIS, BUT NO EVIDENCE HAS BEEN SEEN PROVING EFFORT BEING MADE TOWARD THIS ISSUE.  SEAT BELTS WILL NOT PROPERLY RETRACT!  MANY 3000GT AND STEALTH OWNERS HAVE THIS PROBLEM.  THIS MUST BE ADDRESSED IMMEDIATELY!  WHEN THE BELT IS BUCKLED USUALLY ONLY THE LOWER HALF IS TIGHT ENOUGH TO RESTRAIN PASSENGER AND DRIVER.  FOR THE AVERAGE HEIGHT DRIVER THIS MEANS A SUDDEN STOP (OR CRASH OF COURSE) WILL RESULT IN HIS OR HER HEAD SLAMMING INTO THE TOP OF THE STEERING WHEEL OR DASHBOARD FOR PASSENGER (YUM, BRAINS ALL OVER MY CAR, CANT WAIT).  MANY 3000GT AND STEALTH OWNERS HAVE FILED THIS COMPLAINT NATIONWIDE AND WE WILL BE HEARD!  THIS IS NOT OF COURSE A THREAT, BUT AN AFFIRMATION THAT WE WILL BE STAYING ON TOP OF THIS UNTIL IT IS PROPERLY HANDLED.  MOST OF OUR BELTS OR NOT WORN, AND LOTS OF US HAVE FOUND (THOSE WHO HAVE CHECKED) THAT OUR BELT SPOOLS ARE IN FACT PROPERLY LUBRICATED BUT YET, STILL WE WOULD BE BETTER OF USING TWINE TO TIE OURSELVES TO THE SEATS.  PLEASE, PLEASE, PLEASE TAKE THIS INTO CONSIDERATION BECAUSE IF OUR BELTS DON'T WORK, THERE REALLY ISN'T ANY REASON FOR US TO EVEN HAVE THEM.  CANT SAY FOR SURE HOW MANY FAILURES, JUST THINK THIS...EVERY TIME.  THANK YOU   *JB

SEAT BELTS IN 1991 MITSUBISHI 3000GT VR4 DO NOT RETRACT!!!  WIDESPREAD ISSUE AMONG 3000GT AND GTO OWNERS!  PLEASE OPEN INVESTIGATION AS THIS IS HIGHLY DANGEROUS SINCE SEAT BELTS DO NOTHING IF THEY FAIL TO CINCH-UP AS DESIGNED.  *NM

TL* - THE CONTACT PURCHASED A 1991 MITSUBISHI 3000GT VR4 DECEMBER 9, 2006.  THE CONTACT STATED THAT WHILE DRIVING AT 75 MPH UNDER DRY ROAD CONDITIONS AND LIGHT TRAFFIC, THE VEHICLE SHOOK AND VIBRATED A FEW TIMES.  THE CONTACT SLOWED DOWN TO STOP THE VEHICLE, WHILE REDUCING SPEED TO 10 MPH THE VEHICLE REAR WHEELS LOCKED CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO SKID ABOUT 20 FEET.  NO ONE WAS STRUCK OR INJURED DURING THIS INCIDENT.  THE VEHICLE WAS TAKEN BY FLAT BED TRUCK TO A LOCAL SHOP WHERE THE DRIVE SHAFT WAS REMOVED ALLOWING THE WHEELS TO MOVE.  THERE WAS A TRACE OF LIQUID ON THE TRANSFER CASE THAT HAD A BURNT SMELL.  THE CONTACT FOUND OUT ABOUT THE RECALL WHILE RESEARCHING WWW.3SI.ORG.  THERE IS A RECALL ON THE TRANSFER CASE AND RELATES TO OIL LEAKING OUT THAT MAY CAUSE THE REAR WHEELS TO LOCK.  THE CONTACT CALLED MITSUBISHI IN REGARDS TO THE RECALL.  MITSUBISHI INFORMED THE CONTACT OF A RECALL ISSUED IN JAN 2003. THE  REPAIRS FOR HIS CAR WERE MADE JULY 8TH 2003.  MITSUBISHI EXPLAINED THAT THEY COULD NOT PAY FOR THESE REPAIRS SINCE THE VEHICLE WAS ALREADY SEEN FOR THE RECALL.    THE CONSUMER STATED PAID OVER $2,000 FOR REPAIRS. UPDATED 08/13/07  *TR

WHILE NOTHING SERIOUS HAS COME OF MY ISSUE YET, THE POTENTIAL IS THERE. MY 91 MITSUBISHI 3000GT (WITH 72,000 MILES) IS HAVING PROBLEMS RETRACTING IT'S SEAT BELT. I NOTICED IT WAS A SAFETY ISSUE WHEN I WAS FORCED TO SUDDENLY STOP (DUE TO A CAT CROSSING THE ROAD) AND THE SEAT BELT DID NOT WANT TO LOCK AND RETRACT IN SATISFACTORY TIME. THERE WAS A SIGNIFICANT AMOUNT OF SLACK LEFT IN THE SEAT BELT THAT COULD POTENTIALLY CAUSE INJURY IN THE EVENT OF AN ACCIDENT.  WHEN I TALKED WITH MY LOCAL MITSUBISHI DEALERSHIP ABOUT IT THEY TOLD ME THEY WOULD HAVE TO CHANGE OUT THE MECHANISM THAT RETRACTS THE BELT, BUT THAT IT WAS NOT COVERED UNDER WARRANTY. AS A SAFETY ISSUE I BELIEVE IT SHOULD BE A A RECALL AS I HAVE TALKED WITH MANY OTHER 3000GT OWNERS WHO HAVE THE SAME PROBLEM.  *JB

I AM ONE OF THE MEMBERS OF 3SI.ORG WHICH IS A WEBSITE COVERING THE 3000GT/STEALTH MODELS FROM 1991-1999. I HAVE NOTICED THAT A LARGELY SHARED MAJORITY OF US HAVE THE SAME PROBLEM. THE PROBLEM IS THAT THE SEAT BELT DOES NOT RETRACT INTO PLACE WHEN PULLED OUT. THE SEAT BELT IS THERFORE EITHER LOOSE ON THE DRIVER AND PASSANGER WHICH CAN LEAD TO DEATH/INJURY OR WHEN THE PERSON IS EXITING THE CAR THE PERSON HAS TO WIND THE BELT BACK INTO THE POSITION SO IT DOESNT FALL OUT OF THE DOOR. THIS IS A SERIOUS SAFETY ISSUE AND I THINK A MUST FOR RECALL. I WAS IN A ACCIDENT RECENTLY AND THE SEAT BELT DID NOT ENGAGE IN TIME AND I HIT MY HEAD ON THE STEERING WHEEL AND HAD TO GO TO THE ER EVEN THOUGH IT WAS A SLIGHT FENDER BENDER. PLEASE ISSUE AN INVESTIGATION ON THIS BELT. BTW MY CAR HAS ONLY 65,000 MILES AND THE SEAT BELT WORE OUT AT 22,000 MILES.

ON MY 1991 DODGE STEALTH R/T TT I HAVE HAD NUMEROUS OCCASIONS OF A SLACK IN BOTH OF MY SEAT BELTS. THE SEAT BELTS DO NOT RETRACT PROPERLY AT ALL. MOST OF THE TIME THE SEAT BELTS JUST HANG LOOSE AND YOU HAVE MANUALLY TRY AND RETRACT THEM (NOT EASY). THIS IS A HUGE PROBLEM WITH SAFETY. IF I WAS TO GET IN A CRASH THE SEAT BELT WOULD NOT BE ABLE TO FUNCTION PROPERLY. THIS IS SCARY FOR MY PASSENGERS AND MYSELF. IT COULD CAUSE DEATH AND NEEDS ATTENTION. THIS IS AN ON GOING PROBLEM. MY SEAT BELTS AND OTHER OWNERS SEAT BELTS OF THE DODGE STEALTH AND MITSUBISHI 3000GT'S ARE HAVING THE SAME SEAT BELT PROBLEM. THIS ISSUE SHOULD BE FIXED UNDER A RECALL.  *NM

I HAVE A 91 MITSUBISHI 3000GT SL. THE SEAT BELTS IN IT HAVE A PROBLEM LOCKING UP AND NOT RELEASING. THE SEAT BELTS IN MY CAR DO NOT FUNCTION PROPERLY SOMETIMES. WHEN THE SEAT BELT IS PULLED ON IT DOES NOT RETRACT, LEAVING ENOUGH SLACK IN THE BELT THAT IF AN ACCIDENT WERE TO OCCUR, IT WOULD NOT SERVE ITS PURPOSE AS A SAFETY RESTRAINT. IN MY OPINION THIS SHOULD BE INCLUDED IN A LIFETIME WARRANTY. SAFETY WAS AN ISSUE WHEN BUILDING CARS OF THESE TYPES SO THEY SHOULD ALWAYS BE AS SAFE AS POSSIBLE. I HAVE HEARD MANY PEOPLE SAY PUT ARMOR ALL ON THE BELTS AND THEY WILL WORK JUST FINE, BUT LIKE MANY OTHER 3000GT OWNERS I HAVE TRIED THIS AND IT DOESN'T WORK. I HAVEN'T OWNED MY CAR LONG BUT THIS WAS ONE OF THE FIRST THINGS I NOTICED ABOUT MY CAR. IT WOULDN'T BOTHER ME THAT MUCH IF I DIDN'T WEAR MY SEAT BELT THAT OFTEN BUT I NEVER GO SOMEWHERE WITHOUT MY SEAT BELT ON. I ALSO HAVEN'T REALLY DROVE ANYBODY AROUND IN MY CAR SO IM NOT REAL SURE ON HOW THE PASSENGER SIDE OR BACK SEAT BELTS WORK. RIGHT NOW IM JUST HAVING PROBLEMS WITH THE DRIVER SIDE SEAT BELT.  *JB

1. THE CAR HAD NO SIGN OF FAILURE UNTIL THE AUTOMOBILE WAS IMMOBILE.  2. THE FAILURE WAS THE RESULT OF A DEFECTIVE TRANSFER CASE, AND CAUSED THE CAR'S DRIVE TRAIN TO SEIZE.  3. NO ACTIONS WERE TAKEN TO RESOLVE THE FAILURE.  *NM
TRANSMISSION FAILED 2 TIMES ON MY 91 MITSUBISHI 3000GT. *JB

THE SEAT BELT RETURN MECHANISMS ON MY 1991 3000GT VR-4 NO LONGER WORKS PROPERLY WHICH LEAVES SLACK IN THE SAFETY BELT.  IF AN CRASH WERE TO OCCUR WITH THIS SLACK IN THE SEAT BELT THE SEAT BELT WOULD NO LONGER SERVE ITS PURPOSE AS A SAFETY RESTRAINT.  *JB
SEAT BELT FAILS TO RETRACT PROPERLY WHEN SECURED OR UNBUCKLED.  THIS IS THE 3RD MITSUBISHI 3000GT AND STEALTH THAT HAS HAD THIS ISSUE.  *JB

WHEN I PURCHASED MY 1991 MITSUBISHI 3000GT VR-4 IN JUNE OF 2004. THE SEAT BELTS WOULD NOT RETRACT ON THEIR OWN AND WOULD HAVE TO BE FED BACK INTO THE REEL BY HAND. BOTH THE DRIVERS SIDE AND THE PASSENGER SIDE DO NO RETRACT. I HAVE DISASSEMBLED THE ENTIRE UNIT AND ATTEMPTED TO FREE UP AND LUBRICATE IT, BUT THE MECHANISM WAS NOT REPAIRED. IT SEEMS THAT IT IS A FAILURE IN THE DESIGN OF THE SEATBELT AND A STRONGER SPRING IS NEEDED.  THE SEAT BELT NOT RETRACTING POSES A SERIOUS SAFETY RISK AS IN THE EVENT OF AN ACCIDENT THERE WOULD BE NO SHOULDER RESTRAINT.  THIS IS A VERY COMMON PROBLEM AMOUNT 3000GT'S AND DODGE STEALTHS. ALMOST ALL CARS ARE AFFECTED. I BELIEVE THAT A DEALER RECALL SHOULD BE INSTALLED.  *JB

issues.title: Transfer Case Failure
issues.description: The transfer case in VR-4 models is prone to catastrophic failure, often due to worn viscous coupling or inadequate lubrication. This results in complete loss of all-wheel drive functionality and potential damage to the drivetrain.
symptoms: Loud grinding noise from center of vehicle
Metal shavings in transfer case oil
issues.fix_description: Replace transfer case assembly or rebuild with upgraded viscous coupling unit
issues.prevention: Regular transfer case fluid changes every 30,000 miles, avoid aggressive launches

issues.title: Active Aerodynamics System Failure
issues.description: The active front and rear spoilers frequently fail due to worn motors, damaged wiring, or control module issues. The system may get stuck in extended or retracted position.
issues.fix_description: Replace spoiler motors, repair wiring harness, or replace aerodynamic control module
issues.prevention: Regular lubrication of spoiler mechanisms, avoid manual operation

issues.title: Crankshaft Position Sensor Failure
issues.description: The crankshaft position sensor commonly fails, causing intermittent stalling, no-start conditions, and rough idle. This is a known weak point in the 6G72 twin-turbo engine.
issues.fix_description: Replace crankshaft position sensor and inspect wiring harness for damage
issues.prevention: Regular inspection of sensor wiring, avoid excessive heat exposure

issues.title: Turbocharger Oil Line Leaks
issues.description: Oil feed and return lines to the turbochargers are prone to leaking due to age and heat cycling. This can lead to turbo failure and engine oil starvation.
issues.fix_description: Replace all turbocharger oil lines with updated parts or aftermarket braided lines
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, allow proper turbo cool-down time

issues.title: Rear Steering Rack Failure
issues.description: The electronically controlled rear steering system is complex and prone to failure. Common issues include rack seal leaks, control module failure, and solenoid problems.
symptoms: Rear wheels not turning with front
issues.fix_description: Rebuild or replace rear steering rack, replace control module if necessary
issues.prevention: Regular power steering fluid changes, avoid forcing steering when parked

issues.title: Transmission Control Module (TCM) Failure
issues.description: The TCM for the automatic transmission frequently fails, causing erratic shifting, loss of gears, or transmission going into limp mode.
issues.fix_description: Replace or reprogram transmission control module, check wiring connections
issues.prevention: Regular transmission fluid changes, avoid aggressive driving

issues.title: Boost Control Solenoid Failure
issues.description: The boost control solenoids for the twin turbo system frequently stick or fail, leading to overboost or underboost conditions that can damage the engine.
issues.fix_description: Replace boost control solenoids and vacuum lines, clean or replace boost control valve
issues.prevention: Regular cleaning of solenoids, use quality fuel

issues.title: Fuel Pump Failure
issues.description: The high-pressure fuel pump commonly fails, especially in high-mileage vehicles. This can cause fuel starvation under load and potential engine damage.
issues.fix_description: Replace fuel pump assembly, check fuel filter and lines
issues.prevention: Keep fuel tank above quarter full, replace fuel filter regularly

issues.title: Timing Belt Tensioner Failure
issues.description: The timing belt tensioner can fail catastrophically, leading to timing belt slippage or breakage. This is an interference engine, so failure results in severe valve damage.
symptoms: Engine won't start after tensioner failure
issues.fix_description: Replace timing belt, tensioner, and water pump. If valves damaged, requires engine rebuild
issues.prevention: Replace timing belt and tensioner every 60,000 miles

issues.title: ECU Capacitor Failure
issues.description: The electrolytic capacitors in the ECU deteriorate over time, causing intermittent engine issues, poor idle, and starting problems.
issues.fix_description: ECU capacitor replacement service or ECU rebuild with updated capacitors
issues.prevention: Store vehicle in climate-controlled environment when possible

editorial.tagline: Japan's technological tour de force with twin-turbo fury
editorial.hero_blurb: The 3000GT VR-4 was Mitsubishi's flagship supercar killer, packing twin turbos, all-wheel drive, and active aerodynamics into a sleek coupe that could humble Ferraris. This technological showcase proved Japan could build world-class supercars that delivered both crushing performance and cutting-edge innovation.
editorial.essence: The VR-4 represented peak Japanese automotive ambition - a twin-turbo, all-wheel-drive missile wrapped in dramatic bodywork and stuffed with more technology than cars costing twice as much. It was complexity incarnate, but when everything worked in harmony, few cars could match its devastating real-world performance.
editorial.heritage: Born from Mitsubishi's GTO concept and sharing DNA with the Dodge Stealth, the 3000GT VR-4 was the Diamond Star's halo car. It showcased the company's rally-bred all-wheel-drive expertise and turbocharging prowess during Japan's economic bubble era when automakers threw caution to the wind.
editorial.design_philosophy: Maximum technological integration in pursuit of ultimate performance. The designers crammed active aerodynamics, electronically controlled suspension, four-wheel steering, and twin turbos into a package that looked like it belonged in a sci-fi movie, prioritizing capability over simplicity.
editorial.motorsport_history: While not a dominant racing force, the 3000GT competed in IMSA GT and Japanese touring car series. Its all-wheel-drive system and turbo V6 were derived from Mitsubishi's rally success, bringing competition-proven technology to the street.
editorial.engine_character: The twin-turbo 6G72 delivers power in violent, addictive surges once the turbos spool. It's not the smoothest V6, but the explosive mid-range punch and distinctive turbo whoosh make every acceleration feel like an event. Heat soak can be an issue during spirited driving.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 5-speed manual offers mechanical precision with a somewhat notchy feel typical of Japanese boxes from the era. Shifts require deliberate inputs but reward smooth technique. The clutch is heavy but progressive, befitting the car's serious nature.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The all-wheel-drive system masks the car's 3,800-pound heft remarkably well, providing tremendous traction and stability. The electronically controlled suspension adapts between comfort and sport modes, though the car always feels substantial and planted rather than nimble.
editorial.steering_feel: Variable-ratio power steering that's heavier at low speeds but lightens up nicely at highway pace. The four-wheel steering system adds stability at high speeds but can feel artificial during parking maneuvers. Feedback is adequate but not particularly communicative.
editorial.brake_confidence: Large Brembo brakes provide strong initial bite and excellent fade resistance. The ABS system is intrusive by modern standards but the overall stopping power is impressive for a heavy GT car. Pedal feel is firm and confidence-inspiring.
editorial.sound_signature: The twin-turbo V6 produces a distinctive growl punctuated by turbo whoosh and wastegate chatter. It's not the most melodious engine note, but the mechanical symphony of boost building and releasing is intoxicating. The exhaust note is purposeful rather than pretty.
editorial.ideal_owner: Tech-savvy enthusiasts who appreciate mechanical complexity and don't mind maintenance challenges. Perfect for collectors who want a piece of '90s supercar exotica with genuine performance credentials and unique character.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Anyone seeking simplicity, low maintenance costs, or easy servicing. The VR-4's complexity can be overwhelming for casual owners, and finding qualified technicians familiar with the numerous electronic systems can be challenging.
editorial.buyers_summary: Find the best-maintained example you can afford and budget heavily for preventive maintenance. The VR-4 rewards knowledgeable ownership but punishes neglect severely. When properly sorted, it remains one of the most capable and distinctive grand tourers ever built.
